# Getting started: build, train and use a convolutional neural network

This is a quick tutorial to show how to build and train you first convolutional neural network (CNN)

## Pre-requisites

- Have **at least 20-100 images** along with their segmentation masks (the more images the better...)
- Make sure the **quality segmentation** is **good and unbiased**
- Copy the original images to a folder named 'input'
- Copy the ground truth segmentation masks to a folder named 'outputGT'
- Ensure you have the same number of files in the 'input' and 'outputGT' folder. Ideally the files should have the same names in both folders (or at least make sure that they are in the same alphabetical order)
- Set aside a few input images the model will never see during the training in an 'unseen' folder (you will use those to see how well the model performs on unseen/unknown data, this is to ensure the model is not overfitting)  

## Build a new model

- Go to the **'Model' tab**
- In the 'Model' box, **select 'Build a new model'**.

<img src="data:image/png;base64, " />

![](./0.png?raw=true "Optional Title")

- **(Optional)** Change the model architecture or the encoder layer

<img src="data:image/png;base64, " />

![](./1.png?raw=true "Optional Title")

- Press **'Go'** at the bottom of the current tab.
- **Congratulations you have just created your first CNN.** Note that the 'train' and 'predict' tabs are now active.   

## Training the model

- Go to the **'Train'** tab
- In **'Compile/recompile model'** select **'Adam'** as the **optimizer** (Adam is a good start). Select **'bce_jaccard_loss'** as the **loss** and press **'+'** to add **'iou_score'** as the **metric** (this loss and metric good choice for binary images)

- <img src="data:image/png;base64, " />

![](./2.png?raw=true "Optional Title")



- In the **'Training dataset'** box:

- <img src="data:image/png;base64, " />

![](./3.png?raw=true "Optional Title")

 
    - press **'+'** (a window pops up)
    
- <img src="data:image/png;base64, " />

![](./4.png?raw=true "Optional Title")
  
    - In the **'Input' tab** of this window, drag & drop your input folder into the 'dataset' field (the number of detected images will now be displayed along with a green sign if everything went fine)
    
- <img src="data:image/png;base64, " />

![](./5.png?raw=true "Optional Title")
    
    - In **'Channel number adjustment'**, select the **'Channel of interest'** from your input image (visually check the preview if you are unsure about channel number) (**NB:** this step is optional if input images are single channel images, mandatory otherwise)
    
    <img src="data:image/png;base64, " />
    
    - Similarly, select the **'Output'** tab of the popup window
    - Drag & drop your 'outputGT' folder into the 'dataset' field
    - Choose a channel if appropriate
    - Press **'Ok'** and the window will close


- In **'Data augmentation'**:
    - press **'+'** select **'None'** and press **'Ok'**
    - press **'+'** select **'Flip'** and press **'Ok'**
    - press **'+'** select **'Translate'** and press **'Ok'**
    - If your segmentation is 1 px wide (e.g. watershed mask, then stick to these three augmentations, otherwise you may add 'shear', 'zoom' and 'rotate')
    
    <img src="data:image/png;base64, " />
    
    ![](./6.png?raw=true "Optional Title")
    
- In **'Tiling'** set **'Default tile width'** and **'Default tile height'** to 256

<img src="data:image/png;base64, " />

![](./7.png?raw=true "Optional Title")

- In **'Normalization'** keep the parameters unchanged (images will be normalized to a 0-1 range)

<img src="data:image/png;base64, " />

![](./8.png?raw=true "Optional Title")


- In **'Training parameters'** verify the **'Output models to'** field and change it if necessary. Feel free to change other parameters such as **'Epochs'** (i.e. the number of iterations of the model over the dataset) if needed. Check that **'best model'** is loaded upon **training completion**.

<img src="data:image/png;base64, " />

![](./9.png?raw=true "Optional Title")

- Press **'Go (Train model)'**
- **Wait several seconds to days depending on the size of your training dataset and the power of your GPU**
- **Congratulations you have trained your first CNN**

## Use the created model for prediction

- Go to the **'Predict'** tab
- **Drag & Drop** your 'unseen' folder onto the 'Dataset' field

<img src="data:image/png;base64, " />

![](./10.png?raw=true "Optional Title")

- In **'Channel number adjustment'** select the 'Channel of interest' if your input has several channels (a preview of the channel is available below)

<img src="data:image/png;base64, " />

![](./11.png?raw=true "Optional Title")

- Press **'Go (predict)'** at the bottom of the tab and wait a few seconds/minutes
- Browse your 'unseen' folder, EPySeg predictions can be found in a folder named **'predict'**.
- **Congratulations you have now completed your first training**

**PS:** if you are not happy with the results, try increasing the size of your training set, or train the model longer and/or try different architectures/backbones combinations.
